<TITLE> Messi rescues Barca, United stay top </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Feb 2 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Lionel Messi came off the bench to score two goals as Barcelona maintained their huge lead in the Spanish Primera Liga. Manchester United kept the chasing pack in England at bay with a 1-0 defeat of Everton while Hoffenheim's dream debut season in the Bundesliga continued when they went two points clear. ENGLAND Manchester United made it 12 consecutive clean sheets in the Premier League with a 1-0 victory at home to Everton as they strengthened their grip on the title race. Cristiano Ronaldo's penalty was enough to seal the points while Edwin van der Sar set a new English record for keeping the ball out of his net, beating the 18 hours 23 minutes achieved by Reading's Steve Death 30 years ago. United are two points clear of Liverpool with a game in hand after Liverpool beat Chelsea 2-0 on Sunday thanks to late goals from Fernando Torres. Chelsea are five points off the pace, along with Aston Villa who were held 0-0 at home by Wigan. Stoke City moved out of the bottom three with a 1-0 home defeat of Manchester City, who ended the weekend by signing Newcastle United keeper Shay Given. SPAIN Lionel Messi came off the bench to rescue the points for Barcelona as they came from behind for a 2-1 win at Racing Santander, to maintain their healthy advantage in the Primera Liga. Messi made the difference when he came on in the second half scoring both goals to take his tally for the season to 16. Champions Real Madrid are keeping pace 12 points behind the leaders with their 2-0 win at Numancia on Saturday, making it six wins from six. They pulled six points ahead of third-placed Sevilla. Misfiring Sevilla, Villarreal and Atletico Madrid all dropped further from contention with defeats. ITALY AC Milan were the only team from the top three to win at the weekend with on-loan David Beckham setting up two goals in a 3-0 win at Lazio, which pushed the Rossoneri up to second. Alexandre Pato converted a Beckham cross shortly before the break and Massimo Ambrosini headed in the Englishman's perfect free kick early in the second half. Kaka added a late third. Leaders Inter Milan, who maintain a six-point advantage, drew 1-1 at home to lowly Torino thanks to a Nicolas Burdisso equaliser following Rolando Bianchi's excellent header. Juventus slipped to third after suffering their second defeat in a row when they lost 3-2 at home to in-form Cagliari. Genoa remain fourth thanks to Domenico Criscito's 88th minute goal in a 1-0 home win over Palermo. FRANCE Girondins Bordeaux put a foot at the top of the Ligue 1 ladder on Sunday but slipped back to second to seven-times champions Olympique Lyon three hours later. Both teams were playing at home and both were held, 2-2 by Lille and 1-1 by St Etienne respectively. The two games were tense and at the end of 22nd round of games, Lyon, on 43 points, kept ambitious Bordeaux a point behind. It was a bad day for Olympique Marseille. They lost 1-0 at lowly Sochaux and lost third place to Paris St Germain who recorded a solid 2-0 win over Caen on Saturday. GERMANY Hoffenheim continued their dream first season in the Bundesliga, opening up a two-point gap to Hertha Berlin and Hamburg SV at the top of the table with a convincing 2-0 win over relegation-threatened Energie Cottbus. Hertha, second on goal difference, struggled to beat Eintracht Frankfurt 2-1 while Hamburg SV edged past Bayern Munich 1-0. Champions Bayern have dropped to fourth on 35. Improving Bayer Leverkusen, who drew 1-1 at Borussia Dortmund, are in the title hunt on 33 while Werder Bremen's troubled season continued when they went down 2-1 at home against lowly Arminia Bielefeld to slump to 10th place. NETHERLANDS Moussa Dembele and Mounir El Hamdaoui scored second-half goals to earn AZ Alkmaar a 2-0 victory at Sparta Rotterdam and stretch their on top of the Dutch league to nine points with 14 matches remaining. Second placed Ajax Amsterdam suffered their second straight defeat at home against Heerenveen, with Danijel Pranjic on target, while Ajax finished with 10 men for the third match in a row after a straight red card for Thomas Vermaelen. Twente Enschede failed to move into the second place after being held to a 0-0 draw by Utrecht, while PSV Eindhoven registered their first win of 2009 beating lowly Graafschap Doetinchem 3-0. SCOTLAND Former England skipper Terry Butcher made a great start to life as manager of Inverness Caledonian Thistle with a 0-0 draw against Scottish Premier League leaders Celtic. Butcher's bottom-placed side avoided a ninth straight defeat while Celtic had their lead cut to two points over Rangers who beat third-placed Dundee United 2-0 on Saturday. Fourth-placed Hearts lost to Hamilton while St Mirren began life at their new St Mirren Park stadium by drawing 1-1 with Kilmarnoc
